According to the current plan document from **May 7, 2026**, the architecture has moved in the right direction: full legal rows, terminal-only tactical facts, a graph/set encoder, legal-cell embeddings, cell-marginal and conditional proposal views, cheap pair retrieval, a rich biaffine pair scorer, sampled pair candidates, Gumbel root admission, progressive widening, and candidate-aware targets. That broadly matches the research-report intent: **search acts on unordered pairs, while the network uses factorized structure to propose pairs and a symmetric scorer to rank them.** 

My critical review: **direct pair retrieval is a good idea, but only if it is treated as a recall-oriented candidate source, not as the final policy and not as a reason to score all pairs naively.** The current branch’s actual pair machinery is still much weaker than the plan: it has pair heads and pair-row scoring, but current pair candidate generation can still devolve into legal-order first-N pair scoring, which the latest plan correctly rejects.  

## 1. Current state of the model architecture and pairs

The current graph direction is correct. The model represents the state as variable-size objects: `STATE`, `TURN`, `STONE`, `LEGAL`, and `WINDOW6`. That is the right abstraction for an unbounded board where legal actions are row-table objects rather than crop pixels. The docs also correctly say pair actions should not become graph attention tokens by default because legal pairs are `O(A²)` for `A` legal actions; pair rows should reference existing legal-cell token vectors instead. 

The current branch’s pair heads are:

```text
policy_pair_first:
  one logit per legal first-placement row

policy_pair_joint:
  one logit per canonical unordered first-placement pair row

policy_pair_second:
  one logit per known-first second-placement row
```

The current `policy_pair_joint` is a symmetric MLP over features like `state`, `h_i + h_j`, `|h_i - h_j|`, and `h_i * h_j`. That is a reasonable baseline, but not the final architecture. The research context itself flags a stronger design: a full legal-row interaction scorer, such as biaffine or pointer-style scoring. 

The current code agrees with that picture. `GlobalHexGraphNet` has `policy_place`, `policy_pair_first`, `policy_pair_joint`, and `policy_pair_second`; the joint pair scorer concatenates symmetric features and sends them through an MLP. It is symmetric at the feature level, but it does not yet have the explicit low-rank biaffine relation term the final plan wants. 

The current pair strategy is also not yet true pair-action MCTS. `PairStrategy.score_graph_pair_chunks` can score pair rows, but when it builds full-turn pairs it walks legal rows in nested-loop order and stops at `max_pairs`. That makes the candidate set depend on legal-row ordering. It is a debug scaffold, not a strong pair candidate selector. 

The latest plan correctly rejects that current behavior:

```text
Rejected: Legal-Order First-N Pair Scoring As Candidate Selection
```

That rejection is important. The pair scorer may score a supplied pair set, but it should not define that set by first-N legal-order enumeration in self-play or evaluation. 

## 2. Is direct pair retrieval a good idea?

**Yes, but with caveats.**

Direct pair retrieval solves a real weakness of marginal/conditional proposal: some strong pairs are not composed of two individually obvious cells. In Hexo, a pair may matter because of the relationship between the two cells: covering two threats, completing a 4-window, creating a double threat, or linking two windows. The research report explicitly says many important decisions are not “which single cell is best?” but “which two cells together create, complete, or cover the right set of windows?” 

So I like the plan’s direct-pair-retrieval idea:

```text
h_i = legal_cell_embedding(i)
u_i = W_u h_i
v_i = W_v h_i

s_prop(i, j) =
  0.5 * (u_i · v_j + u_j · v_i)
  + cheap_pair_features(i, j)
```

The plan is also right to say this is a **retrieval signal**, not the final policy. It should form a bounded candidate set; the richer `pair_joint_logits` scorer and MCTS decide among admitted pair candidates. 

The applicable external template is biaffine relation scoring. Dozat and Manning’s biaffine parser is not a game-playing paper, but it is strong evidence that learned bilinear/biaffine scoring is a mature way to score pairwise relations between variable elements. Hexo pair scoring is a relation-scoring problem over legal cells, so the analogy is valid. ([OpenReview][1])

Maximum-inner-product retrieval is also relevant as an implementation pattern: low-rank retrieval can find large entries in products of two vector tables more efficiently than arbitrary pair MLP scoring. That supports direct pair retrieval as a **candidate generator**, especially if legal rows grow large. ([University of Mannheim][2])

But I would **not** make direct pair retrieval the dominant or sole source at the start. It can collapse just like any model-led source. Early retrieval vectors will be poorly trained. If the selector becomes “top-k by direct retrieval,” the system can permanently hide good pairs from search. The plan already recognizes candidate-source quotas and small canary/diversity sources as support-collapse protection. 

My verdict:

```text
direct_pair_retrieval = good as a primary model-led candidate source
direct_pair_retrieval = bad as the only candidate source
direct_pair_retrieval = bad if it silently becomes exhaustive all-pair scoring
direct_pair_retrieval = bad if its sampled support is trained as if complete
```

## 3. Is the candidate building pipeline optimal?

**No. It is directionally right, but not yet optimal.**

The latest plan has the right components:

```text
terminal_exact_v1
direct_pair_retrieval
policy_pair_rerank
anchor_conditioned_completion
structured_exploration
blind_canary
```

It also correctly requires pair candidate metadata: source contributions, beta/inclusion estimates, forced flags, tactical flags, terminal-equivalence flags, and target-prune flags. 

But I would refine the pipeline in three ways.

### Change 1: separate retrieval, reranking, and search

The plan currently says `direct_pair_retrieval`, `policy_pair_rerank`, and `anchor_conditioned_completion`. That is right, but the boundaries need to be sharper:

```text
PairCandidateSelector:
  builds candidate rows and source metadata

PairScorer:
  scores supplied rows with cheap retrieval and rich joint scores

SampledJointPairStrategy:
  consumes admitted candidates in Gumbel/PUCT/MCTS
```

This separation prevents a repeat of the current branch problem where pair scoring and candidate construction are intertwined. The current `PairStrategy` is too close to doing both. 

### Change 2: direct retrieval should be two-tiered

I would use:

```text
cheap_pair_retrieval_score:
  high-recall candidate discovery

rich_pair_joint_score:
  expensive final pair prior over admitted rows
```

The cheap retrieval score should be low-rank and GPU-friendly. The rich scorer should use a stronger biaffine-plus-feature architecture:

```text
pair_joint_logit(i,j) =
  cell_marginal_i
  + cell_marginal_j
  + symmetric_biaffine(h_i, h_j)
  + MLP(pair_features, state_context)
```

This `m_i + m_j + R_ij` decomposition is important. It lets the model learn “this cell matters” from dense marginal signal while separately learning “these two cells have synergy.” The research notes explicitly warn that pure sparse pair training can starve the single-cell representation and collapse onto sampled candidates. 

### Change 3: candidate selection should optimize recall, not just score

For the candidate selector, the metric should not be “does the model’s top pair look good?” It should be:

```text
candidate recall of the best pair search would want
```

Concretely, evaluate:

```text
terminal pair recall
large-budget audit-search best-pair recall
top-N exhaustive small-state recall
D6 consistency of selected pair sets
source-specific hit rates
wall-clock pair candidates per second
final MCTS value improvement from each source
```

The candidate selector’s job is not to be the final policy. Its job is to keep the true good pair inside the candidate set often enough that search can improve it.

## 4. Is the move selection pipeline optimal?

**Not yet.**

The final move selection must be:

```text
root search posterior over unordered pairs
-> choose pair
-> apply both stones atomically
```

The current branch still has code that can project pair logits back onto single-action logits via `pair_logits_to_action_logits`. That is fine as a diagnostic or auxiliary marginal, but it should not be the final move-selection path. 

The plan’s pair action contract is right: after the opening, the search action is an unordered canonical pair of two distinct legal cells, with stable row identity, D6 validation, and terminal-equivalence metadata. 

I would strengthen the move-selection contract with this explicit rule:

```text
The selected root object is PairAction.
Cell marginals may be logged, displayed, or trained as auxiliary targets.
They may not be used to independently choose the two placements after pair search.
```

If the implementation has to call Rust `place(a)` then `place(b)` because of API shape, that is an execution detail. The decision must already be fixed as `{a,b}` before the first placement is sent.

## 5. Studies that are directly applicable

Several studies are relevant, but they support different parts of the plan.

**Gumbel AlphaZero / Gumbel MuZero** supports the root-admission decision. The paper’s key point is that AlphaZero can fail to improve its policy when the search does not visit all root actions; it proposes sampling actions without replacement and reports improvements when planning with few simulations. That maps directly to Hexo’s sampled pair-root problem. ([OpenReview][3])

**Sampled MuZero** supports proposal-aware sampled action subsets. The ICML paper frames exactly the issue here: action spaces may be too large to enumerate, so policy evaluation/improvement must work over sampled subsets. The important lesson is not learned dynamics; it is that sampled-action planning needs proposal-aware correction and target construction. ([Proceedings of Machine Learning Research][4])

**Set Transformer** supports the object/set encoder direction. It is designed for permutation-invariant set inputs and models interactions among set elements with attention, including scalable attention variants. Hexo’s stones, legal cells, and windows are naturally variable-size set/graph objects. ([Proceedings of Machine Learning Research][5])

**Pointer Networks** support the anchor-conditioned completion head. Pointer Nets were designed for variable-size output dictionaries where outputs correspond to positions in the input sequence. That is exactly the shape of “choose a completion cell from the legal-cell table conditioned on an anchor.” ([NeurIPS Papers][6])

**Deep biaffine attention** supports the pair scorer. It is a mature example of scoring relations between pairs of variable elements with a biaffine classifier. This does not prove it will beat all alternatives in Hexo, but it is a strong architectural prior for a legal-cell pair scorer. ([OpenReview][1])

**Action branching / factored action-space work** is relevant mostly as a caution. Action branching scales high-dimensional discrete actions by decomposing the action into branches, but Hexo’s pair value is often coupled. That literature supports factorized proposal views, not replacing pair-value backup with independent cell decisions. ([Mendeley][7])

**Factored MCTS** is also cautionary. It explicitly addresses large factored state/action spaces and combines MCTS with product-of-marginals approximations, but the paper itself frames the method as scalable and sometimes heuristic under strong technical assumptions. In Hexo, where pair synergy is central, pure factorization should be a helper, not the main semantics. ([AAAI Publications][8])

## 6. My strongest critique of the current plan

The current plan is broadly correct, but it risks overloading the candidate selector.

Right now, `direct_pair_retrieval`, `anchor_conditioned_completion`, `policy_pair_rerank`, `structured_exploration`, and `terminal_exact_v1` are all listed as sources. That is good. But the plan should specify the **dataflow order** more rigidly:

```text
1. Full legal rows
2. Encode graph once
3. Produce legal-cell embeddings
4. Produce cell marginal / completion / retrieval scores
5. Build broad pre-candidate pool from sources
6. Canonicalize and deduplicate
7. Score pre-candidates with rich pair_joint scorer
8. Select final candidate set by quotas + score
9. Root Gumbel admission or interior progressive widening
10. Pair-action MCTS
11. Candidate-aware target emission
```

Without this order, an implementation can accidentally let `pair_joint` define candidates by scoring first-N pairs, or let direct retrieval score too many pairs, or let marginal heads choose the final move.

The plan should also explicitly say:

```text
direct_pair_retrieval is a recall source, not a policy target source.
```

The policy target comes from search improvement over admitted pair candidates, with proposal metadata and pruning. The latest plan already requires proposal-aware PUCT and forbids raw model logits over a sampled set unless the sampling assumption is recorded. 

## 7. What I would change in the plan

### A. Rename `policy_pair_rerank`

I would rename it to:

```text
rich_pair_rerank
```

or:

```text
pair_joint_rerank
```

The word `policy` is too easy to confuse with “this is the final action distribution.” It is not. It is the rich pair scorer over a candidate row set.

### B. Make direct retrieval exact-blockwise before approximate

Do not start with approximate nearest-neighbor or complex MIPS infrastructure. Start with:

```text
blockwise exact top-k over legal-cell embedding products
```

For typical debug sizes, a blockwise matrix product is easier to test, easier to D6-validate, and less likely to have silent retrieval bugs. Approximate retrieval should be a later optimization if profiling proves it is necessary.

### C. Add retrieval-specific tests

Required tests:

```text
D6 transform preserves retrieved pair set up to canonical transform.
Diagonal pairs i=i are impossible.
(a,b) and (b,a) never both survive dedup.
Terminal pairs are protected even if retrieval score is low.
Late-legal-row winning pair is retrieved or protected.
Direct retrieval does not depend on legal-row order except tie-breaks.
Top retrieved pairs are stable under batching/chunking.
```

### D. Add retrieval recall metrics

Add these metrics to artifacts:

```text
direct_retrieval_recall@K_vs_exhaustive_small_state
direct_retrieval_recall@K_vs_large_budget_search
candidate_pool_recall_by_source
terminal_protection_recall
pair_rerank_gain_after_retrieval
source_ablation_Elo_or_winrate
```

### E. Keep cell marginal and completion heads, but demote their names

The model should still have dense cell and conditional proposal views, because the reports say the best model is three-headed: single-cell proposal, conditional second-cell proposal, symmetric joint pair reranker. But the plan should keep the final names away from legacy single-move semantics. Use:

```text
cell_marginal_logits
pair_completion_logits
pair_joint_logits
```

not:

```text
policy_place
policy_pair_first
policy_pair_second
```

The research report explicitly says the single-cell head is for proposal and auxiliary signal, not the final move. 

## 8. Final opinion

**Direct pair retrieval should stay in the plan.** It is probably the most important addition beyond marginal/conditional proposal because it gives the model a pair-native way to surface pairs where neither cell is a top standalone move.

But the final architecture should not be:

```text
direct retrieval chooses the move
```

It should be:

```text
direct retrieval improves candidate recall
rich pair scorer ranks candidates
Gumbel/PUCT search improves candidates
candidate-aware targets train the model
```

The current candidate-building and move-selection pipeline is **not optimal yet** if it remains close to the branch’s legal-order first-N pair scoring or pair-to-single marginal projection. The latest plan is much better because it rejects legal-order first-N, separates full `LEGAL` rows from `ADMITTED_PAIR` rows, and introduces direct pair retrieval plus proposal-aware search. 

My final recommendation:

```text
Keep:
  global graph/window encoder
  legal-cell embeddings
  cell marginal auxiliary/proposal head
  anchor-conditioned completion head
  direct pair retrieval
  rich symmetric biaffine pair scorer
  terminal_exact_v1 only
  source quotas
  Gumbel root admission
  progressive widening
  proposal-aware targets

Change:
  make direct retrieval blockwise-exact and recall-measured first
  rename policy_pair_rerank -> rich_pair_rerank
  separate CandidateSelector from PairStrategy
  forbid pair-to-single projection for final move choice
  require retrieval recall metrics and source ablation evidence

Reject:
  current legal-order first-N pair candidate generation
  direct retrieval as a sole top-k policy
  pair-only sparse target training
  approximate retrieval before exact retrieval is debugged
```

That gives you a new model/search architecture that is faithful to the research reports and significantly stronger than the current code path.

